'''Kenneth C. Bucchi''' was a captain in the [[United States Air Force|US Air Force]] for six years. He fought in the Gulf War and worked four years as both a private and undercover corporate investigator. He has authored books on his experiences and holds a B.S. in Criminology and Political Science from [[Murray State University]].<ref name=truelies/>

He claimed to have been a [[CIA]] narcotics officer, but this was later denied by the CIA.<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement by CIA Spokesman Bill Harlow|url=https://www.cia.gov/news-information/press-releases-statements/press-release-archive-2001/pr04262001.html|publisher=[[Central Intelligence Agency]]|accessdate=27 June 2014|date=April 26, 2001}}</ref> He previously convinced various media that his story was true, being interviewed on [[CNN]], [[Greta Van Susteren]]'s talk show, and [[Fox News Channel]]'s [[Bill O'Reilly (political commentator)|Bill O'Reilly]].<ref>{{cite news|title=True Lies? |author=Coker, Matt |url=http://www.ocweekly.com/features/features/true-lies/22610/?page=1 |work=OC Weekly |date=2001-06-28 |accessdate=2008-04-03 }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Howard Jurtz |title=CNN's Very Secret Agent: CIA Says Man's Story Is Phony |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-441439.html |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=April 26, 2001 |accessdate=2008-03-25 }}</ref>

